DialogueEditorPhaseObject.text: Are you looking to live here--what is it have you come for?

choices.string: I'm looking to understand the world.

DialogueEditorPhaseObject.text: You'll be sure to find happiness here, my lad. All of us who live here do it in peace and harmony.
Wealth in coin you won't be finding here, our richness comes from something we place more value in: peace.
I'm not sure that answer will come easily! But try if you may. There is something to learn here.
Please, let me welcome you into the city. I'm sure you will find something about it that suits you.
I hope to see you again!

Welcome, stranger! You've happened upon the grand city of Omelas, the place of my ancestors and children to come. I've not seen a visitor in some time--and all who have come desired to become residents.
Oh, good day.

Ah, you're back! I take it you saw the flute player in the plaza. His music always draws in quite the crowd--I don't see it clearing up for a long time. Why not spend some time in the library in the meantime?

A child...? Oh, in the tower? Truth be told, I almost decided to leave Omelas when I learned fully of her when I was young and impressionable. On deeper introspection, however, I decided to stay. It will be your choice.
Good to see you again!

choices.string: I heard talk of a child in a tower.

DialogueEditorPhaseObject.text: Hello, I don't recognize you. Are you a resident-to-be? Fancy a drink? Drooz, perhaps?

choices.string: I could go for a drink.

DialogueEditorPhaseObject.text: Drink? Drooz?
I think I hear a flute coming from the plaza; at the fork, it's the upper path.
No problem. Enjoy the festival, I'm sure I'll be seeing you around.
Here you are. Enjoy the festival, I'm sure I'll be seeing you around, sir.

From where you're from, I gather drugs and such mind-altering subjects are met with law and enforcement. Addiction can be fueled by a poor situation in life--but here, reality is often better than what drooz offers. Still, on a great day such as this, some favor it. Care to try it?

choices.string: Thank you, but I think I'm okay.

DialogueEditorPhaseObject.text: There you are.
Suit yourself. Have a nice day, sir.
Okay.
Drink up.
Take this.
Okay.

I see you're back from the plaza! I've seen him play many a time in the past--he's a skilled young man. Musical performance is commonplace here, when you become a resident I'm sure you'll come out often to listen!

choices.string: I wouldn't mind hearing it again.
Seems a bit excessive to me.

DialogueEditorPhaseObject.text: I should have gone! Ah well, there's always the next event. In Omelas, there is always some sort of festivity in the near future. You should join us for the next one, stranger.
Is that so? Well, I think you'll begin to like it! No where else but Omelas can you be certain to have a calendar filled with celebration. I think you should join us next time!
I'll be seeing you soon, stranger! I'll make sure to get in touch with you so you can attend the next festival with us.
Good day! Welcome to the library of Omelas. I take it you're here to seek information about residency.
But first I'd like to know, what did you think of the flutist, stranger? He's one of my sons--I couldn't be prouder.

The festival in summer may just be my favorite festival of all seasonal festivals. With the coming of each season, we have one, as all times are times of celebration! How can I help you on this great day?

choices.string: I'm curious about that tower I saw.
I'd like to come to understand more about society.
How can I come to live here?

DialogueEditorPhaseObject.text: Is that so? Perhaps you would enjoy the Festival of Fall, or Spring, or even Winter more. Do you have any questions for me?

choices.string: That tower...I saw it from afar. What is it?
How can I come to live here?

DialogueEditorPhaseObject.text: No opinion? Well, he'd probably be the first one to agree with that opinion. My son, too, is more quiet.
Did you see the flute player in the plaza? Please, go see, and tell me how it was!
The tower...well. We can talk about it more after you've become a resident.

choices.string: How can I come to live here?

DialogueEditorPhaseObject.text: We govern ourselves. We simply do not have room in our society for unpleasantness. I think this is the ideal setup for a community.
You'd like to become a resident? Truly, I am overjoyed to hear that!
Why not become a resident? We would love to have you.
Is that so? This is a utopia. We have achieved peace. What more could you want?

choices.string: Hmm...perhaps you're right. Suffering is not necessary.
Suffering is part of being human.

DialogueEditorPhaseObject.text: A child in a tower, you say? Well...I suppose it's something you will come to understand when you become a resident. It is for the good of all of us.

choices.string: That doesn't sound right to me.

DialogueEditorPhaseObject.text: Well...there's not much information I can offer on it. You see, it's a rite of passage for young ones here. As they reach the age of where we think they may be able to understand, they are brought to the child in the tower. There's not much more I can offer you than that unless you become. I apologize.
It is bred of neccessity. If you became a resident, you would be told its secret...
Become a resident, you can find out more.
As the performance ends, the flute player stands, and takes a bow.
The flute player has finished playing, and the crowd is bustling and loud. It's so lively that it's too difficult for you to reach the other side of the plaza.
The bustling crowd dies down as the flute player begins to play. You stop and listen.
Oh, don't mind my son! He's a silly little boy. There is nothing in there.
Mommy, I want to see the thing in the tower!
Oh, it's nothing. My son must have heard it from someone at the playground--they're always joking about things.
But mommy! Why is it in the tower? I want to see it! They told me it's really scary!

choices.string: Your mother said there is no such thing.
Ma'am, what is your son talking about?

DialogueEditorPhaseObject.text: Yes, listen to the nice man. Things in a tower, I simply do not know what you are on about, dear. Perhaps we should head home. It was nice meeting you, sir. It seems my husband has taken a liking to you--you'd be welcome to join us here come next festival.

Well...he...he's not talking about anything! Just a silly story his friends made up. The tower is only for adults, so of course the children assume the worst. You may come to know of it, stranger, if you join us here in Omelas. It was nice meeting you, and it seems my husband has taken a liking to you! We'll be heading home soon, so take care.
We're about to leave, but I'm sure we'll be seeing you again soon!
